tain\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"SessionStart\",\"hookName\":\"SessionStart:clear\",\"command\":\"cmux claude-hook session-start\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"e6e96aca-cc07-4000-920a-8de17962f8e7\",\"toolUseID\":\"e6e96aca-cc07-4000-920a-8de17962f8e7\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:51:43.301Z\",\"uuid\":\"f5891495-3939-443f-91a7-502d09622f81\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"f5891495-3939-443f-91a7-502d09622f81\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"7682603d-1d7b-49cc-900b-ee77433e7db4\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"toasty-stargazing-mountain\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"SessionStart\",\"hookName\":\"SessionStart:clear\",\"command\":\"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks-handlers/session-start.sh\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"e6e96aca-cc07-4000-920a-8de17962f8e7\",\"toolUseID\":\"e6e96aca-cc07-4000-920a-8de17962f8e7\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:51:43.301Z\",\"uuid\":\"bf7bce03-12bd-4c3a-8832-c016f174dd86\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"bf7bce03-12bd-4c3a-8832-c016f174dd86\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"7682603d-1d7b-49cc-900b-ee77433e7db4\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"toasty-stargazing-mountain\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Implement the following plan:\\n\\n# Switch Kiro CI auth from SIGV4 to device-flow token\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nSIGV4 auth was never ported to `kiro-cli-chat` — the binary ignores `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` entirely (upstream issues: kirodotdev/Kiro#5938, aws/amazon-q-developer-cli#1051 both open). The workaround is device-flow auth: run `kiro-cli login --license free --use-device-flow` locally, then store the resulting token JSON as a GitHub secret (`KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN`). In CI, write it to `~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json` so `kiro-cli-chat` picks it up automatically.\\n\\n## Changes\\n\\n### 1. `.github/workflows/e2e-isolated.yml`\\n\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Configure AWS credentials (Kiro OIDC)\\\" step (lines 39-44) — no longer needed\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Setup Kiro CLI\\\" step (lines 46-52) — no longer needed\\n- **Add kiro back** to the \\\"Install agent CLI\\\" case block (manual install, same pattern as before)\\n- **Add new step** \\\"Inject Kiro auth token\\\" that writes `KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN` secret to `~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json`\\n- **Remove** `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` and `AWS_REGION` env vars from bootstrap/test steps (no longer relevant)\\n\\n### 2. `.github/workflows/e2e.yml`\\n\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Configure AWS credentials (Kiro OIDC)\\\" step (lines 87-92)\\n- **Add new step** \\\"Inject Kiro auth token\\\" (same as above)\\n- **Remove** `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` and `AWS_REGION` env vars from bootstrap/test steps\\n- **Keep** the existing kiro install block (already has `mkdir -p`)\\n\\n### 3. Both workflows — new step template\\n\\n```yaml\\n- name: Inject Kiro auth token\\n  if: <agent> == 'kiro'\\n  run: |\\n    mkdir -p ~/.aws/sso/cache\\n    echo \\\"$KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN\\\" > ~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json\\n  env:\\n    KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN }}\\n```\\n\\n### 4. Permissions cleanup\\n\\n- **Remove** `id-token: write` from `e2e-isolated.yml` — only needed for AWS OIDC which we're removing\\n- **Keep** `id-token: write` in `e2e.yml` — used by the full matrix which may have other OIDC needs\\n\\n### 5. Kiro version\\n\\nUse version `1.27.0` (the version confirmed to exist on S3 in earlier testing).\\n\\n## Pre-requisite (manual, one-time)\\n\\n1. Run locally: `kiro-cli login --license free --use-device-flow`\\n2. Copy the token: `cat ~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json`\\n3. Add as GitHub secret `KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN` in the repo settings\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nPush and run the `e2e-isolated` workflow with `agent=kiro` from the GitHub Actions UI.\\n\\n\\nIf you need specific details from before exiting plan mode (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/alisha/.claude/projects/-Users-alisha-Projects-wt-kiro-oneshot/127f24d2-01c3-4b68-a901-0efcaade7632.jsonl\"},\"uuid\":\"c10ec579-96be-4a01-ba53-082a0e4d0595\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:51:42.842Z\",\"planContent\":\"# Switch Kiro CI auth from SIGV4 to device-flow token\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nSIGV4 auth was never ported to `kiro-cli-chat` — the binary ignores `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` entirely (upstream issues: kirodotdev/Kiro#5938, aws/amazon-q-developer-cli#1051 both open). The workaround is device-flow auth: run `kiro-cli login --license free --use-device-flow` locally, then store the resulting token JSON as a GitHub secret (`KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN`). In CI, write it to `~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json` so `kiro-cli-chat` picks it up automatically.\\n\\n## Changes\\n\\n### 1. `.github/workflows/e2e-isolated.yml`\\n\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Configure AWS credentials (Kiro OIDC)\\\" step (lines 39-44) — no longer needed\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Setup Kiro CLI\\\" step (lines 46-52) — no longer needed\\n- **Add kiro back** to the \\\"Install agent CLI\\\" case block (manual install, same pattern as before)\\n- **Add new step** \\\"Inject Kiro auth token\\\" that writes `KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN` secret to `~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json`\\n- **Remove** `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` and `AWS_REGION` env vars from bootstrap/test steps (no longer relevant)\\n\\n### 2. `.github/workflows/e2e.yml`\\n\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Configure AWS credentials (Kiro OIDC)\\\" step (lines 87-92)\\n- **Add new step** \\\"Inject Kiro auth token\\\" (same as above)\\n- **Remove** `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` and `AWS_REGION` env vars from bootstrap/test steps\\n- **Keep** the existing kiro install block (already has `mkdir -p`)\\n\\n### 3. Both workflows — new step template\\n\\n```yaml\\n- name: Inject Kiro auth token\\n  if: <agent> == 'kiro'\\n  run: |\\n    mkdir -p ~/.aws/sso/cache\\n    echo \\\"$KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN\\\" > ~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json\\n  env:\\n    KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN }}\\n```\\n\\n### 4. Permissions cleanup\\n\\n- **Remove** `id-token: write` from `e2e-isolated.yml` — only needed for AWS OIDC which we're removing\\n- **Keep** `id-token: write` in `e2e.yml` — used by the full matrix which may have other OIDC needs\\n\\n### 5. Kiro version\\n\\nUse version `1.27.0` (the version confirmed to exist on S3 in earlier testing).\\n\\n## Pre-requisite (manual, one-time)\\n\\n1. Run locally: `kiro-cli login --license free --use-device-flow`\\n2. Copy the token: `cat ~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json`\\n3. Add as GitHub secret `KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN` in the repo settings\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nPush and run the `e2e-isolated` workflow with `agent=kiro` from the GitHub Actions UI.\\n\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c10ec579-96be-4a01-ba53-082a0e4d0595\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"7682603d-1d7b-49cc-900b-ee77433e7db4\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"toasty-stargazing-mountain\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_0161EmFCDr3kDdsXw2cfA3BW\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"Let me start by reading the two workflow files to understand their current state.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":25431,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":25431},\"output_tokens\":9,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkg3RqLAq8AeX1sZwUmK\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"ff6d5d4e-bafc-4458-a06c-91fac7b7d200\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:51:47.739Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\