rt sqlite3, os\\ndb = sqlite3.connect('$DB')\\ndb.execute('INSERT OR REPLACE INTO auth_kv (key, value) VALUES (?, ?)',\\n           ('kirocli:odic:device-registration', os.environ['KIRO_DEVICE_REG']))\\ndb.execute('INSERT OR REPLACE INTO auth_kv (key, value) VALUES (?, ?)',\\n           ('kirocli:odic:token', os.environ['KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN']))\\ndb.commit()\\n\\\"\\n\\n# 4. Point kiro-cli-chat at the test DB and verify\\n# NOTE: kiro-cli-chat uses XDG_DATA_HOME or platform default.\\n# On macOS it uses ~/Library/Application Support/kiro-cli/\\n# We can test by temporarily moving the real DB and symlinking,\\n# OR just verify the DB contents are correct:\\nsqlite3 \\\"$DB\\\" \\\"SELECT key, length(value) FROM auth_kv;\\\"\\n# Expected: both rows present with reasonable value lengths\\n\\n# 5. On Linux (CI), the path is ~/.local/share/kiro-cli/data.sqlite3\\n# kiro-cli-chat should find it automatically via XDG_DATA_HOME default\\n```\\n\\n## Verification on CI\\n\\nPush and run `e2e-isolated` with `agent=kiro`. The `kiro-cli-chat whoami -f json` at the end of the inject step will fail fast if auth doesn't work.\",\"originalFile\":\"# Switch Kiro CI auth from SIGV4 to device-flow token\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nSIGV4 auth was never ported to `kiro-cli-chat` — the binary ignores `AMAZON_Q_SIGV4` entirely (upstream issues: kirodotdev/Kiro#5938, aws/amazon-q-developer-cli#1051 both open). The workaround is device-flow auth: run `kiro-cli login --license free --use-device-flow` locally, then store the resulting token JSON as a GitHub secret (`KIRO_AUTH_TOKEN`). In CI, write it to `~/.aws/sso/cache/kiro-auth-token.json` so `kiro-cli-chat` picks it up automatically.\\n\\n## Changes\\n\\n### 1. `.github/workflows/e2e-isolated.yml`\\n\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Configure AWS credentials (Kiro OIDC)\\\" step (lines 39-44) — no longer needed\\n- **Remove** the \\\"Setup Kiro CLI\\\" step (lines 46-52) — no longer needed\\n- **Add kiro back** to the \\\"Install agent CLI\\\" case block (man